<br>
Bush has set a policy goal of removing Saddam Hussein from power.  With chaos in the middle east, there is no chance of that happening.  The presence of Israeli military in Gaza is doing the following:<br>
<br>
a) Breeding even more hatred of Israel among the arabs than before (not directly important, but worth keeping in mind)<br>
<br>
b) Destroying any chance whatsoever of any kind of 'peace' to come out of the situation in any reasonable amount of time (reasonable meaning within Bush's term so he can get working on Iraq).<br>
<br>
c) Putting strategic partners of the US in some very bad straights, because for good or ill, most muslims equate Israel with the US.  There are some nasty protests going on, and some pundits think that governments could fall, particularly that of Jordan.  Also, there have been violent protests in Oman(?), the HQ of the US 5th fleet.<br>
<br>
d) Putting us at odds with our european allies - did you notice that at the news conference the other day, Tony Blair didn't mention anything about removing Saddam from power after Bush did?  That in itself is telling as to the strain that the US support of Israel is putting on our relationships with other countries.<br>
<br>
a+b+c+d= No move against Saddam Hussein<br>
<br>
This is in addition to the horrible humanitarian crisis that is just dying to happen in Palestine, as well as the almost-Martyr status that Arafat has gained in the middle east.  If you thought he was a bear to negotiate with before, I can't imagine wht it's going to be like in the future.  It was possible that moderates within the PA could have taken control from him (or gained it when he died), but now there is no room for them to criticize him.<br>
<br>
